04 May 2018 08:00






I like this one, but LeafE was partially right about the science.

Mature  ova are indeed only produced a couple at a time, so that part works. There are considerably more immature ova present at any given time, but the fact that in most women, only one will be brought to maturity and viability at any given time might actually be more of a problem for this skip than an overage of supply. Maybe the village happens to have been originally populated by a lineage that tends towards multiple births?

The particular kind of thelytokous pregnancy mentioned would function as LeafE stated- it would not produce a clone of the mother, but a child with a random set of pairs from the mother's DNA. Unless the mother was homozygous for everything, there would be at least some changes likely.

Changing the type of thelytokous pregnancy would solve both problems. Instead of two eggs merging to provide a double set of DNA similar to that in sexual reproduction, have one egg spontaneously duplicate its haploid set into a diploid set, which would be inherently homozygous, then proceed as a normal embryo. As soon as the village began relying on the spring for reproduction, this would lead to the situation described in the text, with only genetic drift causing any variation whatsoever between generations.







